A little blue heron is a bird species that belongs to the heron family, Ardeidae. 
It can grow up to 70 cm in height and has a wingspan of up to 100 cm. 
The little blue heron has a blue-gray plumage with a dark purple-blue head and neck. 
It has a long, pointed bill that is blue-gray in color with a black tip. 
In flight, the little blue heron displays a broad, rounded wing shape and a slow, steady flapping style. 
The species is often found in wetlands, swamps, and marshes throughout the Americas. 
Little blue herons are known to feed on small fish, crustaceans, and insects.
